How Much Memory Does a Java Thread Take?  

A memory, which is taken by all Java threads, is a significant part of the total memory consumption of your application. JVM does not aggressively size committed memory to the (number of threads * 1MB), that's a wrong assumption based on the wrong NMT reporting where in Java 8 committed memory is automatically set to reserved memory. There are a few techniques on how to limit the number of created threads, depending on whether your application is CPU-bound or IO-bound.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Waste-Free Coding:
Zero-Cost Abstraction 

Do you know where the main areas of waste exist in a Java application and the patterns that can be employed to reduce them? The concept of zero cost abstraction is introduced, and that many optimizations can be automated at compile time through code generation. This article documents how to solve an event processing problem in a highly efficient manner through the reduction of waste in the software stack.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Extending Abstract Classes With Abstract Classes in Java 

In this great article Peter Verhas demonstrates how designing with inheritance can introduce maintenance complexity in our code and make it hard for the readers to have a clear overview of who is calling who.

 
 
 
 
 

A Look at The Optional Datatype in Java
and Some Anti-Patterns When Using It 

The purpose of Optional, introduced in Java 8, is to express the potential absence of a value with a data-type instead of having the implicit possibility to have an absent value just because null-reference exists in Java. In this article, they talk about experiences, gathered while working with Java’s Optional-datatype. During their daily business, they've encountered some “anti-patterns”. In the author's experience if you strictly avoid having those patterns in your code, chances are high that you will come to a cleaner solution.

 
 
 

5 Primary Key Mappings for JPA and Hibernate Every Developer Should Know 

Mapping a primary key column with JPA and Hibernate is simple. You just need to add an attribute to your entity, make sure that its type and name match the database column, annotate it with @Column and you’re done. What is the easiest way of creating a primary key automatically? UUID Keys? If you are interested in the different types of primary keys and what is the best way to create them, make sure to check out this article!

 
 
 
 
 

Optimistic Locking Version Property
With JPA and Hibernate 

In this article, you are going to see how optimistic locking version property works when using JPA and Hibernate.Most often, we overlook basic concepts and focus only on more advanced topics such as associations or queries, without realizing that basic mappings can also have a significant impact when it comes to persistence effectiveness and efficiency. 

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Modern Garbage Collection: Part 2 

Yet another great article about garbage collection. It reviews the different approaches used by ZGC and Shenandoah and compares these modern garbage collectors to the one used in Go in order to prove that garbage collection design is not straightforward as it seems and JVM is leading far ahead.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

The 10 Common Concurrency Models by Jack Shirazi 

Concurrency Models are high level concurrency frameworks designed to help you build your multi-core application faster with fewer concurrency bugs. But there are quite a few of them. Want to know whether you should use Locks? Atomics? Actors? Fibers? Functional? Events? Data Parallelism? Futures? Grids? So many choices! In this whistle-stop tour of the 10 most common concurrency models used in Java, Jack Shirazi explains what’s available, and what their strengths and weaknesses are.

 
 
 
 
 

Test Driven Development: Theory and Practice 

As of today, test-driven development (TDD) is an integral practice in many software projects. However, this practice is still difficult to master and presents significant challenges and risks if not applied right. In this article the idea of test-driven development is discussed, some common pitfalls that you should avoid, and also the impact of test-driven development on design. 

 
 

On the Road to Mastery

 
 
 
 
 
 

Reflection in Java

In this article you can explore java reflection, which allows to inspect or/and modify runtime attributes of classes, interfaces, fields and methods. This particularly comes in handy when you don’t know their names at compile time. Additionally, you can instantiate new objects, invoke methods and get or set field values using reflection. You will also cover the Java Reflection API and look at how to use reflection to inspect classes, interfaces, fields and methods at runtime without prior knowledge of their internals by compile time.

 
 
 

A Quick Guide to Using Keycloak with Spring Boot 

Keycloak is an open source Identity and Access Management solution targeted towards modern applications and services. If you want to learn more about Keycloak, in this article, you are going to read the basics of setting up a Keycloak server, how to connect a Spring Boot application to it, and how to use it with Spring Security. You will see how to use the Admin Console of Keycloak for setting up and then connecting to Spring Boot using the Keycloak Client Adapter.
